  "prompt": "Who is Amartya Sen?",
  "response": "Amartya Sen is an Indian economist and philosopher who is renowned for his contributions to welfare economics, social choice theory, economic and social justice, economic theories of famines, and measures of well-being and poverty. Born on November 3, 1933, in Santiniketan, India, Sen has had a distinguished academic career that includes teaching positions at the University of Calcutta, the Delhi School of Economics, the London School of Economics, the University of Oxford, and Harvard University.\n\nHe was awarded the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences in 1998 for his work in welfare economics, particularly for his contributions to understanding the causes of famine and poverty, and his development of the capability approach, which assesses economic development in terms of enhancing human capabilities rather than merely increasing income or output.\n\nSen has also been an influential voice in public debates on issues such as gender inequality, education, health care, and democracy. Among his many published works are \"Poverty and Famines: An Essay on Entitlement and Deprivation\" (1981), \"Development as Freedom\" (1999), and \"The Idea of Justice\" (2009).",
